Author::::<a href="http://social.ndtv.com/groups.php?id=723564" target="_blank">Avdhut Kulkarni</a>

Comment::::<div class="com_user_text">
                            "Give it up" campaigns for LPG subsidy or any other such subsidies may not be the right solution for its respective intended purpose for following reasons.<br/>
1. Very high campaign costs. It will be interesting to know how much we, the Government, are spending for running such campaigns against the revenues targeted &amp; generated by giving up the subsidies. Incidentally many people tend to look up at such campaigns as a cover up ops for some kind of political advertisement. <br/>
2. It will be further interesting to know how much percentage of the revenue to be generated as above will be spent as administrative expense (including the campaign expenses) &amp; how much of it will be left out for addressing the intended purpose.<br/>
3. If above figures are ever to be published, people who are really concerned for the charity cause, will most likely try some other options offering minimum administrative expenses.<br/>
4. Alternative &amp; more effective way to achieve the intended results may well be that we, the Government, offer subsidy based on income class. We, the government, will then be able to avoid unnecessary subsidy outgo for the affluent classes in the first place. This saving would be much larger than the revenues to be generated from the "Give up subsidy" campaigns on any given day. And there won't be any need for the costly "Give up subsidy campaigns". Of course, nobody can then accuse the Government of inefficient spending Tax-payers' money.
